05:12.120 --> 05:16.800
As you may remember, I was one of the United States delegates to the NATO Parliamentarians'

05:16.800 --> 05:22.280
Conference when it met in its annual session in Paris last fall.

05:22.280 --> 05:26.360
At this meeting I was elected chairman of the Political Committee.

05:26.360 --> 05:30.040
There was a great debate on the floor of the conference over the necessity of having

05:30.040 --> 05:35.800
some means of attaining greater unity among the members of the NATO Alliance.

05:35.800 --> 05:41.160
It would be surprising to have very, very strongly our allies feel about this subject.

05:41.160 --> 05:46.440
And I believe that many people here in the United States still feel to realize how very

05:46.440 --> 05:48.800
serious it is.

05:48.800 --> 05:53.880
Among our allies, the Suez problem is still strongly etched in their members.

05:53.880 --> 05:57.320
This Suez crisis almost wrecked NATO.

05:57.320 --> 06:02.040
At that time you will remember Britain and France to whom they oil through the Suez is even

06:02.040 --> 06:05.120
more important than it is to us.

06:05.120 --> 06:08.720
Along with Israel, the Suez Canal.

06:08.720 --> 06:13.040
We didn't even know there was going to be an attack and our nation ended up on the other

06:13.040 --> 06:16.360
side, on the side of the Soviet Union.

06:16.360 --> 06:21.480
Since in NATO we are all in an alliance together, all of whose members are supposed to support

06:21.480 --> 06:24.000
the other in matters of defense.

06:24.000 --> 06:28.880
You can see how serious a situation like the Suez is to the very basis and to the heart

06:28.880 --> 06:30.640
of NATO.

06:30.640 --> 06:34.880
And while we were meeting in Paris, while this very subject was being debated on the

06:34.880 --> 06:38.600
floor of the conference, we had another such incident.

06:38.600 --> 06:44.320
This one involved a shipment of small arms to Tunisia by Britain and the United States.

06:44.320 --> 06:50.760
At a time when the French thought that Tunisia was helping the Algerian rebel, in the retrospective

06:50.760 --> 06:53.840
time this seems like a small incident.

06:53.840 --> 06:59.360
But many of the great tragedies in wars of history have been caused by small incidents.

06:59.360 --> 07:03.800
And once again, it could have been avoided if there had been proper consultation among

07:03.800 --> 07:05.960
various allies.

07:05.960 --> 07:11.080
From all of this debate, the Political Committee, at the NATO Parliamentarians' conference,

07:11.080 --> 07:16.680
produced a resolution calling for a two-pronged study of ways by which greater unity might

07:16.680 --> 07:22.400
be obtained on the political and economic side of our NATO problems.

07:22.400 --> 07:26.960
The manner by which this resolution might be made effective is one of the subjects of

07:26.960 --> 07:32.120
the Executive Committee meeting in Bonn on Monday and Tuesday of this week.

07:32.120 --> 07:37.040
That is why it's necessary for me as one of the authors of the resolution and as chairman

07:37.040 --> 07:40.320
of the Political Committee to be an attendant.

07:40.320 --> 07:45.080
The resolution calls for the appointment of a citizen's conference, composed of leading

07:45.080 --> 07:48.360
private citizens from all of the 17 NATO nations.

07:48.360 --> 07:54.000
To make a thorough study of this problem and to recommend to their respective nations

07:54.000 --> 07:57.200
as well as the NATO, what might be done.

07:57.200 --> 08:01.600
I would think of their study as something akin to the Hoover Commission's studies.

08:01.600 --> 08:06.240
These citizens on the Hoover Commission made some far-reaching recommendations which

08:06.240 --> 08:10.280
has done a great deal for the government here in the United States.

08:10.280 --> 08:14.680
Most of their recommendations were found feasible and were adopted by Congress.

08:14.680 --> 08:15.680
Some few weren't.

08:15.680 --> 08:18.520
So it would be with the citizens' conference.

08:18.520 --> 08:21.280
We have nothing to lose, much to gain.

08:21.280 --> 08:26.080
The second prong of this proposal would be a hay-piped conference of citizens meeting

08:26.080 --> 08:32.800
in 1959, the 10th anniversary of NATO, and discussing the recommendations of the citizens'

08:32.800 --> 08:39.920
conference, bringing the meeting of NATO home to every citizen in all of our countries.

08:39.920 --> 08:45.360
This is something that needs to be done in the schools at the Civic Club, and in wherever

08:45.360 --> 08:50.440
people talk so that they understand the meaning and the importance of NATO.

08:50.440 --> 08:55.640
I hope that some concrete progress toward getting these conferences underway will be accomplished

08:55.640 --> 08:57.760
at this meeting this week.

08:57.760 --> 09:03.240
After the bond meeting, the President of the NATO conference, Colonel JJ Fenns of the Netherlands,

09:03.240 --> 09:08.600
Mr. Jeffrey D. Freighties, a member of Parliament of Great Britain and I, are scheduled to have a

09:08.600 --> 09:15.080
conference with Mr. Paul Unraised back, the Secretary of NATO about the same problem.

09:15.080 --> 09:19.080
You know, in an alliance like NATO, which is the greatest hope of the free world against

09:19.080 --> 09:23.960
communist aggression, all of the members, all of all of the countries are in the same

09:23.960 --> 09:25.960
canoe, so to speak.

09:25.960 --> 09:28.720
We therefore have to paddle in the same direction.

09:28.720 --> 09:33.640
Our efforts will be to get all of the pedals operated by the Americans that British,

09:33.640 --> 09:38.160
the French, and the Netherlands, and so on, operating in unity.

09:38.160 --> 09:39.840
I hope that we can do it.

09:39.840 --> 09:41.640
Thank you, and goodbye until next week.

09:49.080 --> 10:00.280
Ladies and gentlemen, friends of Tennessee, I just returned from the meeting I discussed

10:00.280 --> 10:06.760
